# =============================================================================
# .trivyignore — deliberately-accepted findings, with justification
#
# These are NOT unreviewed suppressions. Each entry is an intentional
# architectural decision documented in the README's "Security notes &
# deliberate trade-offs" section. Everything Trivy flags that is genuinely
# fixable (SNS/S3 encryption) has been fixed in code rather than ignored here.
# =============================================================================

# AWS-0104 — "Security group rule allows unrestricted egress to any IP address."
# Accepted: both the EC2 and RDS instances need outbound internet for OS/package
# patching (dnf update), and RDS uses it for managed backups/telemetry. Locking
# egress to specific CIDRs is impractical for a general-purpose app server and
# for AWS-managed RDS endpoints (which span large, changing IP ranges). Inbound
# is already tightly restricted (least-privilege ingress); egress-open + tight
# ingress is the standard posture for these tiers. In a locked-down environment
# this would be replaced with egress via a proxy/NAT with allow-listed
# destinations.
AWS-0104

# AWS-0164 — "Subnet associates public IP address."
# Accepted for the DEV baseline only. The public subnets host the internet-
# facing web tier by design. This is already toggleable: set enable_alb = true
# to move the instance to a private subnet behind an ALB with no public IP
# (see the "Production topology" section of the README). The subnet-level
# map_public_ip_on_launch remains true because the subnet is, by definition,
# the public tier; instance-level exposure is what the toggle controls.
AWS-0164
